Use of External Data as Prior Information

However, with Bayesian methods, we know that the prior can sometimes overwhelm the current data if there isn’t a lot of it. And, FDA doesn’t want the prior to overwhelm the current data.

Therefore, we often recommend some type of down-weighting of the prior data in the analysis, or protection against the prior overwhelming the current data, if the results from the current study don’t end up being consistent with prior results. This may be accomplished via “dynamic borrowing”.

So, the amount of information to leverage or the strength borrowed is determined after seeing some or all of the current trial data. We will reduce the strength if there is conflict between the prior and current data.

Finally, even if we use Bayesian methods, our center computes operating characteristics in the frequentist long run. So, we report type I error rate and power.

  • Taking advantage of prior information (e.g., prior studies) can potentially reduce the sample size needed for a new trial.

  • Possible sources of prior information:
    • previous studies, foreign clinical data, in-silico models, similar population

  • Bayesian methods can be used to formally incorporate prior information

  • The prior information should not overwhelm the current study
    • Down-weight strength of prior data via dynamic borrowing
    • Borrowing strength diminishes if there is conflict between prior and current data

Types of leveraging methods

This slide mentions some methods we have seen or used to borrow across studies or data sources. Most use a type of exchangeability assumption, either study-level or patient-level.

Bayesian hierarchical modeling is often used when there are several studies or several populations, and in these cases, hierarchical models can provide shrinkage estimates of treatment effects in a current study. Our Guidance on Bayesian methods talks about these models in a regulatory setting, and Gene Pennello and I described some hypothetical examples in a 2008 paper.

When there are several subgroups, the modeling can also impose a multiplicity adjustment so that any random highs with small sample sizes are shrunk toward more reasonable estimates.

The pediatric extrapolation guidance (as well as Gray et al.) briefly mentions using a 3-level hierarchical model for making inferences about a pediatric population using adult studies. Current research is extending the modeling to treat age continuously and modeling IAs with treatment effect.

However, when you have only one prior study, a viable approach is the power prior method. I will spend more time on how we have used this later.

Then, there are other approaches that we haven’t seen much, but can be useful.

adaptive or dynamic borrowing + Allows protection against over-reliance on prior information that is overly optimistic or pessimistic for current study parameters.

STOP

Combining studies: Estimate device effect in current study by borrowing strength from related studies (prior information). Not the typical meta-analytic overall estimate

Subgroups: Estimate device effect in a subgroup by borrowing strength from related subgroups.

Combining historical and concurrent controls: Borrow from a historical control, and enroll some current control subjects (or, use a predictive control)

  • Bayesian hierarchical modeling
    • Multiple studies, populations or subgroups
  • Commensurate prior (Hobbs & Carlin); Meta-analytic predictive approach (Neunschwander, et al.)
  • Power prior method: Good with a single prior data source (Ibrahim & Chen)
    • Discount Power Prior to integrate “virtual patients” into a clinical trial (Haddad, Thompson et al. 2017)
    • Borrowing is adaptive or dynamic: Depends on similarity of outcomes between prior and current studies.

Review of Conditional Power Prior (CPP)

The methods use the conditional power prior.

So, first, I will give a brief review of notation for the CPP, and its interpretation wrt borrowing from a prior study.

  1. Given a prior dataset D0, as well as a fixed value a0, the power prior on theta, the parameter of interest is:.. We power up the LH of D0 using a0

  2. After observing a new set of data (D) with the same underlying parameter as for D0, with likelihood L, the posterior distribution of theta is given… where we’ve added the LH L

  3. More than one prior dataset can be used with the CPP. For example, a second prior dataset D1 could be incorporated into the conditional power prior with another power parameter value say a1

Prior Distribution on \(\theta\) given D0

\[\color{black}{\large{ {\pi ^{CPP}}(\theta |{D_0},\color{red}{\alpha _0}) \propto {L_0}{(\theta |{D_0})^{ \color{red}{\alpha _0}}}\pi (\theta )}, \,\,\, 0 \le \alpha_0 \le 1} \]

Posterior Distribution on \(\theta\) (after observing D)

\[\color{black}{\large{\pi (\theta |D,{{D}_{0}},{{\alpha }_{0}})\propto {{L}_{0}}{{(\theta |{{D}_{0}})}^{{{\alpha }_{0}}}}\pi (\theta ) \color{red}{L(\theta |D)} }}\]

 

Power parameter (\(\alpha_0\)) is a “discounting factor” that down-weights a prior study, from all \((\alpha_0 = 0)\) to none \((\alpha_0 = 1)\)

 

\(\alpha\)0 can convey an effective sample size of the prior study

Discount Prior Method (Haddad et al., 2017)

So, Haddad et al. used the VPM to simulate prior patients.

Here I describe how the power parameter of the CPP was determined.

If we want the amt of borrowing to be based on similarity between prior and curr data sets, then we can’t use a pre-specified power parameter value because the current data are not known.

So we use dynamic borrowing, where a0 is based on the relationship between the prior and current data responses after the current data are observed. So now the power parameter is a function of D and D0.

But, what is pre-specified is the form of the relationship.

In the 2017 paper, we defined this form by a weibull CDF of \(p\).

where if \(\theta\) defines a success rate, say, p is defined as prob(t > t0)…

So, if p is large, you would borrow more from the prior data bc a0 is closer to 1. And, borrowing is conservative because p is the prob that the current success rate is higher than the prior success rate.

You can have a two-sided discount fcn that prevents you from borrowing when prior rate is much worse.

We also limited the amount of borrowing to be a pre-specified maximum. So, this really is a discount prior because borrowing can only be less than a pre-specified fixed amount that one would be willing to use under a perfect scenario.

Prior on \(\theta\) (success rate) given D0 (and D)

\[\color{black}{\large{\pi ^{CPP}(\theta |{D_0},D) \propto L_0(\theta |{D_0})^{\color{red}{\alpha_{0}(D_0,\,D)}}\pi (\theta )}}\]

\[\large{\color{red}{\alpha_{0}(D_0,\,D)} = 1 -\exp(-(\frac{\color{red}{p(D_0,\,D)}}{\lambda})^k) \le M \le 1}\]

where


\(\large{\color{red}{p(D_0,\,D) = p} = P({\theta }>{{\theta }_{0}}|\,{{D}_{0}},\,{D}) = P({\theta }-{{\theta }_{0}} > 0|\,{{D}_{0}},\,{D})}\)

\(\,\,\, \large{\theta}\) ~ \(\large{\pi(\theta | D) \propto L(\theta | D)\pi(\theta)}\)

\(\large{\theta_0}\) ~ \(\large{\pi(\theta | D_0) \propto L_0(\theta | D_0)\pi(\theta)}\) \(\,\,\,\,\,\)

Comments on Discount Prior Method

Some comments that we have heard or identified with the discount prior method are given in this slide. I’m just going to list them now, and address them throughout the talk.

  1. …violates the LH principle because information about theta from D enters not only through the LH, but also through the prior. Why does this matter? When the data are included in two places in an analysis, results might be artificially precise because you’re saying you have more information than you really do.

  2. Because we use dynamic borrowing from prior information, the amount of prior information (effective prior sample size) can change after seeing the current data. And so, it’s not legitimate…I will show how a small variation can make this legitmately Bayesian

  3. Finally, We’ve discovered that …

I’m going to describe some reasoning and variations for potentially addressing the comments. And, then explore some operating characteristics of the variations.

  1. The current data are used twice, both in the prior and in the likelihood. Potential implication to artifically increase precision.

  2. The prior is fully determined a posteriori. (Is this legitimately Bayesian?)

  3. A “stochastic ordering” measure of similarity may be influenced by the current data sample size so that more prior information is borrowed when the sample size is smaller.

“Double Use”: Use an interim subset (\(\small{D_1}\)) in \(\small{\alpha_0}\)

The first modification addresses the double use of current data, that is, using it to determine the amt of borrowing as well in the final inference.

So, instead of using all of the data, we determine the power parameter from a subset or interim information from D.

D1 is like a “second” prior dataset because it comes before D2 and after D0.

Mathematically,…, Doing this helps us call the discount prior method legitimate Bayes.

Suppose,…

The resulting CPP …We do not want to “down-weight” current data. (only L0 is downweighted by a0)

This new CPP shown in expression is like the posterior after observing D1. It then becomes the prior before observing D2 (the remaining subset of D).

Then, after observing D2, the second subset, we get another posterior.

This is an application of “yesterday’s posterior is today’s prior”.

Yesterday’s posterior is after observing D1, today’s prior is before observing D2.

I point out that it is a legitimate prior for \(\theta\) despite it not defining the joint distn of D0, D1, and \(\theta\). Recall that the prior is a distn on \(\theta\), everything else is constant. Only \(\theta\) is random.

Size of D1 is n1 = %n. Then, D = [D1, D2].

 

Prior on \(\theta\) given D0 (and D1):

\[\color{black}{\large{\begin{align} & {{\pi }^{CPP}}(\theta |{{D}_{0}},{{D}_{1}})\propto {{L}_{0}}{{(\theta |{{D}_{0}})}^{{{\alpha }_{0}}({{D}_{0}},\color{red}{{D}_{1}})}}\pi (\theta ) \color{red}{L(\theta |{{D}_{1}})} \\ \end{align}}}\]

Posterior given remaining current data D2:

\[\color{black}{\large{\begin{align} & \pi (\theta |{{D}_{0}},{{D}_{1}},{{D}_{2}})\propto \\ & \,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\, L_0{{(\theta |{{D}_{0}})}^{{{\alpha }_{0}}({{D}_{0}},{{D}_{1}})}}\pi (\theta )L(\theta |{{D}_{1}}) \color{red}{L(\theta |{{D}_{2}})} \\ \end{align}}}\]

If D1 is considered a “second” prior data set, CPP is a legitimate prior on \(\theta\), before observing D2.

Measuring Similarity of Prior and Current Data

In some further exploration, we discovered that the stoch ordering measure depended too much on posterior variance or sample size, and as such, it could be anti-conservative. To illustrate the issue, I use a success rate defn for the parm of interest theta, here.

Theta is the parm that generated the current data, and theta0 is the parm that generated the prior data. I disinguish them here because they are distinguished in the discount function.

Suppose the value of theta that generated the current data is better than the value, theta0, that generated the prior data. Then, with non-informative priors, the posterior distribution of t-t0, where t is given the current data alone, and t0 is given the prior data alone, might look like the LHS figure where the center of t-t0 is the right of 0. This figure shows hypothetical posterior distributions of t-t0 with different colors to indicate different potential posterior variances given different current sample sizes, centered about their respective means.

If we compare the relative posterior probabilities that t-t0 > 0 (which is the similarity measure), shaded for each current data sample size, they will likely be high regardless of the posterior variance of theta, and furthermore, the probability is higher when the posterior variance is lower (current sample size is larger).

However, consider an alternative scenario on the RHS, where the current data are worse than the prior data so that the center of the posterior of t-t0 will be to the left of 0. Here, the prob(t-t0 > 0) (shaded) will likely be higher in the smaller sample cases than in the larger sample cases, leading to a higher measure of similarity, and relatively more borrowing from the prior when the sample size is smaller, at least with a one-sided loss function.

This may be anti-conservative because not only is the current data worse than the prior, but when we have less current data (with the same center), the tendency is to borrow a higher percentage of prior data, which could increase type I error rate.

Using a two-sided discount function does not help. With a two-sided loss function, the power parameter increases with “similarity” up to a point, then decreases in a mirror image. Therefore, for the scenarios on the LHS, the higher sample sizes could end up borrowing less than the lower sample sizes, which is not ideal but is also not anti-conservative. However, for the scenarios on the RHS, because the shaded areas are smaller than on the LHS, and therefore not on the mirror image decline, the smaller sample size will still borrow more than the larger size

Hypothetical Posterior Distribution of \(\small{\theta} - \small{{{\theta }_{0}}}\) for Success Rate

Shaded is \(\small{P(\theta - {{\theta }_{0}} > 0 |{{D}_{0}},D)}\)
Borrow more with smaller
current data sample size (anti-conservative?)

Alternative Measure of Similarity

So, we explored several other measures of similarity (p, in the discount function).

For simplicity and direct comparison with the stoch ordering measures, in this talk, I define similarity using a posterior probability. We calculate the posterior probability that the magnitude of the diff between theta and t0 is within a value delta , where δ is a pre-specified similarity margin.

The similarity margin defines a difference between the current and prior means that would not be clinically meaningful.

And, here, I also use D1 which is an interim subset of D, the full current data.

As in Haddad et al. (2017), theta comes from its posterior distribution given D1 alone, and t0 comes from its posterior distribution given D0 alone.

In addition, we propose that borrowing from the prior will only take place if the observed mean difference between the prior and the interim current data, falls within [-δ, δ]. In this way, the observed mean difference will be consistent with the similarity margin.

\[\color{black}{\large{\pi ^{CPP}(\theta |{D_0},D_1) \propto L_0(\theta |{D_0})^{\alpha_{0}(D_0,\,\color{red}{D_1})}\pi (\theta )}}\]

\[\large{\alpha_{0}(D_0,\,\color{red}{D_1}) = \left\{ \begin{align} & 1 -\exp(-(\frac{p}{\lambda})^k) \\ & p \,\,\, (\text{identity}) \\ \end{align} \right. \,\,\,\,\,\, \le M \le 1}\]

 

\(\large{p = P(|{\theta }-{{\theta }_{0}}| < \color{red}{\delta}|\,{{D}_{0}},\,\color{red}{D_1}), \text{ if} }\) \(\large{\color{red}{|{\bar D_0} - {\bar D_1}| < \delta},}\) else \(\large{p = 0}\)

\(\,\,\, \large{\theta}\) ~ \(\large{\pi(\theta | D_1) \propto L(\theta | D_1)\pi(\theta)}\)

\(\large{\theta_0}\) ~ \(\large{\pi(\theta | D_0) \propto L_0(\theta | D_0)\pi(\theta)}\)

\(\small{\delta}\) is a “similarity margin”: If \(\small{|{\theta }-{{\theta }_{0}}| < \delta}\), current and prior data are “similar”.

Alternative Measure of Similarity

So, if we look at this similarity measure in the same context as before, we have on the LHS the scenario where the current data are better than the prior, but its better by less than delta. So, t-t0 is between 0 and delta.

On the RHS, the current data are worse than the prior data, but the true mean difference still falls within the similarity margin (i.e., t-t0 is greater than -delta). The posterior probability of the difference falling within the equiv region is shaded as before.

Regardless of whether the current data are better or worse than the prior data, the posterior probability appears to be higher when the current data sample size is higher (leading to higher similarity and more borrowing). Furthermore, the similarity will be higher when the current data mean is closer to the prior mean.

Als0, Because closeness is defined with respect to an similarity margin, we do not increase the chance of making a type I error outside of this margin.

However, one must pre-specify the similarity margin. If it is not possible to do so, we recommend other definitions of similarity, or a different way to estimate the power parm.

Simulation Study

We ran a simulation study to evaluate these variations to the discount prior: such as using a percentage of D (referred to as D1) to help determine a0, where the percentage can be less than 100%, and using the equivalence region to define similarity.

We simulated a normally distributed prior data set (D0) with mean 0 and variance 1, and sample size n0= 25 or 100.

  • For current data generation, we selected Normal mean values, \(\theta^{*}\), ranging from – 1 to 0, in increments of 0.25. For each value of \(\theta^{*}\) we simulated 15,000 current data sets (D) from a normal distribution with mean \(\theta^{*}\), variance 1, and size n = 25 or 100.

  • The percentage of D used to form D1 varied from 100% to 25%, in increments of 25%.

  • similarity measures:

  • We examine both type I error rate and power using these settings.

  • Simulations were done using the mpi interface under the R package pbd.

Prior data: \(\small{D_0 \sim N(0,1)}\), sample size \({n_0 = }\) 50.

 

Current data: Normal mean values, \(\small{{{\theta }^{*}}}\): \(\small{(– 1, – 0.75, – 0.5, }\) \(\small{– 0.25, – 0.1, 0, 0.1, ... , 1)}\).

 

For each \(\small{{{\theta }^{*}}},\) simulate 15,000 current data sets D from a \(\small{N({{\theta }^{*}}, 1)}\) with size \(n =\) 50.

 

Percent of D used to form D1: \(\small{100\%, 75\%, 50\%, 25\%}\).

 

Similiarity measure:
\(\delta\)-region: \(\small{p = P(|{\theta }-{{\theta }_{0}}| < \color{red}{\delta = 0.2}|\,{{D}_{0}},\,{D})}\)
stochastic ordering: \(\small{p = P({\theta }-{{\theta }_{0}} < 0 |\,{{D}_{0}},\,{D})}\) .

Form of \(\small{{{\alpha }_{0}}({{D}_{0}},{{D}_{1}})}\) for Simulations

This slide shows the form of the discount function used in the simulations. As for Haddad et al, we used a Weibull CDF, as a function of p (x-axis), the similarity measure. We used both a 1-sided discount function and a 2-sided function for stoch ordering, but only a 1-sided fcn for delta measure.

The specific parameter values of the Weibull were chosen to be the same as those suggested by Haddad et al for some of their examples.

With the 1-sided function, we gradually borrow more as the similarity (determined by p) between the prior and current data distributions increases.

With the two-sided function, whose expression is defined on the right, we borrow more when p increases up to 0.5, then we borrow less as p moves even higher. For the stoch order measure as p, this means that if the current data were much better than the prior data, we stop borrowing, so that we do not borrow from much worse prior data.

Weibull parameters would be pre-specified at the design stage.

\(\small{\color{black}{\alpha _0(D_0,D_1)}}\) by \(\small{{{\theta }^{*}}}\)

Figure shows \(\scriptsize{\alpha_0}\) (borrowing fraction) averaged over the 15,000 data sets, for each \(\scriptsize{\theta^{*}}\) value, when n0 = n= 25,50,100. Different colored lines are for the different percents of D that represent D1.

First is the delta measure, with the identity disc fcn in the top row, and 1-sided Weibull disc func in the bottom row.

  • As \(\scriptsize{\theta^{*}}\) gets closer to the prior mean, we borrow more (\(\scriptsize{\alpha_0}\) increases), and borrow less when \(\scriptsize{\theta^{*}}\) moves away from 0 in the either direction.

Borrowing is highest near the similarity region, and drops toward zero outside of it. This is due to limiting borrowing to when the observed mean difference between the prior and current data falls within the similarity region [-0.2, 0.2].

Finally, we borrow more when we use more current data (% is higher), to determine a0 (percent is higher).

Type I Error Rate under \(\color{black}{H_0: \small{ \theta \le \theta^{*} } }\)

Why do we have higher type i error rate on avg in -0.5 null value, AND it’s higher for 100% line? For -0.5 in general: it’s a unique scenario for n=25 because for some simulations, the observed mean diff will fall within 0.2, and others won’t. So, we end up borrowing if the mean diff falls in that region (there is between 2 and 3% borrowing fraction at theta* = -0.5) . Bc of that, type i error rate increases beyond 2.5%.

It doesn’t for -0.25 because even though it’s close to the similarity region, the null value is also close to the prior mean. The smaller sample size

Because we have a higher avg borrowing fraction

For discarding, with n=25 when you discard 50-75% of the current data, it’s 6-12 obns left. Plus, you’re not borrowing much from the prior. So, it’s pretty close to using a non-inf prior, with mean=0 but variance super high.

Here, I present type I error rate by \(\color{black}{\scriptsize{\theta^{*}}}\) when it is consistent with H0. And l ranges from – 1 to –0.10. So, these are the null values on the x-axis.

LHS of each pair of panels shows type I error rate when we dont discard D1 (i.e., keep it) after using it in \(\scriptsize{\alpha_0}\), and the RHS shows when we do discard D1. Top panel shows n=100, bottom panel shows n=25. First is the delta similarity measure.

For the delta similarity measure we borrowed more from D0 (which is consistent with H1) with more of D used in the borrowing fraction. So, type I error rate tends to increase with a higher % of D being used in \(\scriptsize{\alpha_0}\), despite D coming from \(\scriptsize{H_0}\). So, the 100% line has the highest type i error rate.

Also, because we don’t borrow when the obs mean diff falls outside of -0.2 to 0.2, type I error rate is very low when the null value is < -0.25. Recall that the prior mean is 0. So, this is like the difference in means.

Another point: despite type I error rate being relatively high in the -0.25 to -0.10 region, it’s not that bad that we mistakenly reject the null of <= -0.25 (and conclude that theta > -0.25, when theta= -0.25) if a difference between -0.2 and 0 is considered not clinically meaningful. We might be more concerned with null values -0.5 and lower.

In any event, this relatively higher type I error rate is expected due to borrowing more often in the -delta to delta range.

It’s not relatively higher with the n=25 sample size because borrowing in general is lower then, and due to higher variability with a smaller sample size, we could end up borrowing more from the prior in the -0.75 area because some of the observed mean diffs could be less than 0.2 magnitude. So, you’ll get enough prior data borrowed to reject the null of theta <= -0.75 sometimes even though theta* is pretty far away from 0.

Power under \(\color{black}{H_0: \small{ \theta \le -0.5 } }\)

Bias = \(\small{{E({\theta }| D_0, D) - \theta^{*} }}\)

Summary of discount prior methods

  • \(\delta\)-similarity region measure has less “double use” of the full set of current data in the final posterior, and may depend less on posterior variance.
    • Type I error rate generally highest inside of the \(\delta\)-region, but lower when an interim data percentage was used to estimate the borrowing fraction.
    • Power was higher when using 100% of the current data (vs less than 100%) to estimate the amount of borrowing .

  • Using stochastic ordering measures
    • Somewhat greater power than \(\delta\)-similarity measure
    • Larger increase in bias when current data better than prior data (for 1-sided discount function)
    • Higher type I error rate in region outside of \((-\delta, \delta)\)

Future Directions for VP Model Validation

  • Have several different models that use different types of data sources, then use an “ensemble” method to combine them (similar to the ensembles used in supervised learning). The different data sources may provide different inputs (e.g., bench data won’t provide clinical input, as a previous clinical study would provide).
    In addition, as Xuefeng says, there could be different models from the same data source, where they use different input variables.

  • Because of the step of model selection, there should be another validation step before testing on real clinical data. That validation step should make sure that the chosen model is best by using something like cross-validation. It could be tweaked to ensure a good fit before testing it out on real clinical data.

  • Different data sources would provide different inputs (i.e., complexity and diversity).
  • Use an “ensemble” method to combine the model predictions (e.g., bagging, boosting)

Some Final Thoughts on Leveraging External Evidence

If it were suspected that current data were not as favorable as prior data, or later current data D2 were not as favorable as earlier current data D1.

In the latter case, we would want to borrow less than in the former case. An ordering measure would solve this issue. However, because an ordering measure would use the tails of a distribution, it would depend on variance and thus current data sample size.

  • With more than one prior data source, several potential methods are viable: hierarchical modeling, meta-analytic prior, power prior.

  • With only one prior data source, the discount power prior should be considered.

  • Covariates may be needed to calibrate the prior and current datasets in order to assume exchangeability.

  • Ultimately, investigating design characteristics is necessary to ensure a reasonable trial design.
